The '''Imperial Seal of the Mongols''' is a [[Seal (East Asia)|seal]] ([[tamgha]]-тамга) that was used by the [[Mongols]]. The imperial seals had inscriptions in [[Mongolian script]] or other scripts that used in various Mongol regimes such as the [[Mongol Empire]] and the [[Northern Yuan dynasty]]. [[File:Guyuk khan's Stamp 1246.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Seal (East Asia)|Seal]] of [[Güyük Khan]] using the classical [[Mongolian script]], as found in a letter sent to the Roman Pope Innocent IV. It reads: ''{{lang|mn-Latn|Möngke ṭngri-yin küčündür. Yeke Mongγol ulus-un dalai-in qanu ǰrlγ. Il bulγa irgen-dür kürbesü, büsiretügüi azatuγai}}''.]] According to [[Plano Carpini]], the [[Russians|Russian]] [[handicrafts]]man, Kozma, made a seal for [[Güyük Khan]]. This seal might have been a seal used to stamp the letter to [[Pope Innocent IV]].
[[File:OljeituLetterToPhilippeLeBel1305.jpg|250px|thumb|Translation of Oljeitu's message by [[Buscarello de Ghizolfi]], on the back of the letter (visible here).]]
The [[Poles|Polish]] scholar, Cyrill Koralevsky, shot a photo of the seal in 1920. The prominent [[French people|French]] Mongolist, [[Paul Pelliot|P. Pelliot]], translated the Mongolian scripts on the seal later. However, the Mongolists believe that Kozma made only one of the imperial seals and a seal on the letter is [[Genghis Khan]]'s, which was inherited by his successors.<ref>[http://www.origo.mn/printpdf/285 Их Монгол төрийн Хас эрдэнийн тамга]</ref>
During the [[Yuan dynasty]], which ruled the whole of [[China]], there were several seals. [[Biligtü Khan Ayushiridara|Ayushridar]] had an imperial seal with the script "[[Northern Yuan|Great Yuan]]".{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} In the 16th century, the Mongols used a square-shaped seal. [[Ejei Khan]] gave one of those seals to the Manchus in 1635, who in turn established the [[Qing dynasty]].
[[File:Imperial Seal of Bogd Khan.jpg|250px|thumb|Imperial seal of [[Bogd Khan]] in 1911. From left to right: in [[Soyombo alphabet|Soyombo]], [[Mongolian script|Classical Mongolian]] and [[Phags-pa script|Phags-pa]]]]
[[Bogd Jivzundamba]], ruler of the [[Mongolia (1911–24)|Bogd Khaganate]] had a tamgha (seal) with the inscription "Holiness - Bogd Khaan who holds religion and authority" in the 20th century.
