{{Infobox non-profit |name = India Pride Project |image = |caption = |map = |map_size = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px --> |map_alt = <!-- map alt text --> |map_caption = |map2 = |type = [[Non-governmental organization]] |tax_id = |registration_id = |founded = 2014 |founder = S. Vijay Kumar and Anuraag Saxena |dissolved = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |merged = |successor = |location = |addnl_location = |coordinates = |origins = |key_people = |area_served = India |products = |services = |focus = |mission = |method = |revenue = |disbursed = |expenses = |endowment = |num_volunteers = |num_employees = |num_members = |affiliations = |subsid = |owner = |motto = |homepage = |website = {{URL|http://ipp.org.in/}} |footnotes = }}
'''India Pride Project''' ('''IPP''') is a group of art enthusiasts who uses social media to identify stolen religious artefacts from Indian temples and secure their return. Co-founded in 2014 by two Singapore-based art enthusiasts, S. Vijay Kumar and Anuraag Saxena, it now has activists from all over the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anuraag Saxena: Returning stolen art to India|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uq6b07Ln0Pc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Facebook sleuths bring home India's stolen idols|url=http://www.businesstimes.com.sg/life-culture/facebook-sleuths-bring-home-indias-stolen-idols|website=[[Business Times (Singapore)|The Business Times]]|accessdate=2017-01-05|date=3 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=S Vijay|last=Kumar|title=India Pride Project - How Smuggled Indian Art Is Brought Back Home|url=http://swarajyamag.com/culture/how-smuggled-indian-art-brought-home|website=swarajyamag.com|accessdate=2017-01-05|date=7 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Nirmala|last=Ganapathy|title=Recovering India's stolen art pieces|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/recovering-indias-stolen-art-pieces|website=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=11 November 2018|date=10 November 2018}}</ref>
==Recoveries==
'''[[Sripuranthan Natarajan Idol|Dancing Shiva]]''': In 2014, it helped to secure the return of a US$5 million bronze statue of the Hindu god Shiva from the [[National Gallery of Australia]]. Named ''[[Sripuranthan Natarajan Idol|Dancing Shiva]]'', the statue was stolen from a Tamil Nadu temple and trafficked by [[Subhash Kapoor (art dealer)|Subhash Kapoor]], a former Manhattan art dealer who was later under the United States federal investigation known as Operation Hidden Idol. When the gallery denied the statue was stolen, IPP used the social media to publicize and compare the images of the stolen idol with the one on gallery's display. Since the arrest of Kapoor in 2012, United States has returned to India many artefacts recovered under Operation Hidden Idol.
Ms Donna Yates, a lecturer on antiquities trafficking at the [[University of Glasgow]], believes "the grassroots work of the IPP in documenting cases of theft and bringing them to public attention is crucial - and unmatched anywhere in the world."
'''[[Nalanda]]'s 12th century Buddha''': This six-and-a-half-inch bronze (with traces of silver inlay) of the Buddha seated in the bhumisparsha mudra, was stolen along with 13 other statues 1961 from the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI) site museum in Nalanda.<ref>[https://www.livemint.com/Politics/CQMHtZkX51woQKhGLHlmEO/On-Independence-Day-India-gets-back-its-12th-century-stolen.html On Independence Day, India gets back its 12th century stolen Buddha statue, Aditi Khanna, PTI, LiveMint, Aug 15 2018]</ref> It was noticed at a at a London auction. Fortunately a photographic record of the statue was saved by Sachindra S. Biswas, a retired director general of the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI). Kumar, is attempting to pursue India’s claim on another Buddha statue, suspected to be from the 1961 theft, currently at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art in the US.<ref>[https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/MitejLdBdImh1v8DIM3VWN/How-the-mystery-of-the-Missing-Buddha-statue-was-solved.html How the mystery of the Missing Buddha statue was solved, Bibek Bhattacharya, Aug 21 2018]</ref>
