The '''national colours of Canada''' ({{lang-fr|Couleurs nationales du Canada}}) were declared by King [[George V]] in 1921 to be red and white{{sfn|Canadian Heritage:Official symbols of Canada|2009}} and are most prominently evident on the [[Flag of Canada|country's national flag]]. Red is [[Color symbolism|symbolic]] of England and white of France, the colours having been used representatively by those countries in the past.{{sfn|Canadian Heritage: National Colours - Red and White|2009}} The [[maple]] is one of the [[National symbols of Canada|national symbols]] and red is the first leaf colour after spring budding & also the autumn colour of [[Maple leaf|maple leaves]].{{sfn|Canadian Heritage: The arms of Canada|2009}}

==History==
{{multiple image
| footer    = The Arms of Canada. On the left is the version from 1923, with green maple leaves on a white background in the shield. On the right, a modified version from 1957 with red maple leaves on a white background in the shield.
| image1    = Coat of arms of Canada (1923).jpg
| alt1      = 
| width1    = 166
| image2    =Coat_of_arms_of_Canada_(1957).png
| alt2      = 
| width2    = 140
}}

Canada's national colours can trace their history to the [[First Crusade]] of the 11th century, during which [[Normans|Norman]] nobleman [[Bohemond I of Antioch]] distributed red crosses to the crusaders he led, so that they could affix them to their clothing "as a distinguishing mark".{{sfn|Canadian Heritage:Official symbols of Canada|2009}} Thereafter, nations were identified by the colour of their cross, and in particular, England used a white cross on a red background and France a red cross on white.{{sfn|Canadian Heritage:Official symbols of Canada|2009}} Eventually, France and England agreed to exchange their colours{{fact|date=June 2018}}, and [[St George's Cross]] was adopted as an emblem of England. This was the flag used by [[John Cabot]] when he landed on the island of [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] on his second voyage in 1497 under the commission of [[Henry VII of England]].{{sfn|Canadian Heritage: You were asking...|2009}} The two nations would eventually explore [[North America]], where each claimed territory.

As a result of the [[proclamation]] of the [[Arms of Canada]] by King [[George V]] on 21 November 1921, red and white became Canada's official colours.{{sfn|Canadian Heritage:Official symbols of Canada|2009}} The proclamation stated "''a Royal helmet mantled argent doubled gules''" and "''a wreath of the colours argent and gules''",{{sfn|Canadian Heritage: The arms of Canada|2009}} in which ''[[argent]]'' refers to the colour white or silver, and ''[[gules]]'' to red, [[Tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]] used to [[Blazon|emblazon]] a [[coat of arms]].{{sfn|McCreery|2005|p=73}} In 1957, the Arms of Canada were modified—the maple leaves on the shield were changed from green to red "in recognition of Canada's official colours".{{sfn|Canadian Heritage: National Colours - Red and White|2009}} The proclamation accepts both colours for the maple leaves, stating "''three maple leaves conjoined on one stem proper''",{{sfn|Canadian Heritage: The arms of Canada|2009}} in which "proper" refers to the natural colour of the leaves, which is green in spring and summer, and red in autumn.

It was not until 1961, with the creation of [[Royal standards of Canada#Sovereign's standard|The Queen's Personal Canadian Flag]], that red and white became entrenched as the national colours.{{sfn|Tidridge|2011|p=222}}

==Reproduction==
For the [[Federal Identity Program]] operated by the [[Treasury Board Secretariat]] of the [[Government of Canada]], official and signage colours are specified in [[Specification (technical standard)|technical specification]] T-145.{{sfn|Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat: Colour Values|2012}}

The red colour is named ''FIP red'' and represented by the [[Web colors#Hex triplet|hexadecimal triplet]] ''FF0000'', the 8-bit per [[Channel (digital image)|channel]] [[RGB color model#Numeric representations|RGB value]] ''(255,0,0)'', the [[CMYK color model|CMYK color]] (0,100,100,0), or the [[Pantone#Pantone Color Matching System|Pantone Color Matching System]] colour Pantone 032.{{sfn|Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat: Colour Values|2012}}{{sfn|Industry Canada|2009}}

A second red colour, known as ''safety red'', is also specified but not used for official symbols; it is represented by the hexadecimal triplet E8112D, RGB value (230,15,45), CMYK colour (0,90,75,0), or Pantone colour 185.{{sfn|Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat: Colour Values|2012}}

White is represented by CMYK colour white, and the de facto national colour black is represented as CMYK colour black; six more colours are defined for use by the government.{{sfn|Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat: Colour Values|2012}}

==Uses==

===National flag of Canada===
[[File:Flag of Canada.svg|thumb|right|alt=Two solid red vertical bars on the left and right, each one quarter of the width of the flag. The middle half is white, with an 11-point maple leaf at its centre, approximately 80% of the height of the flag stem to tip, and 80% of the width of the white background on which it rests.|The [[Flag of Canada]] consists of elements using only the national colours.]]
The national flag uses the national colours.{{sfn|Canadian Heritage:Official symbols of Canada|2009}} Its red-white-red pattern is derived from the flag of the [[Royal Military College of Canada]]{{sfn|Montgomery|2013}} and the [[Canada General Service Medal]] of 1899.{{sfn|Canadian Heritage:Official symbols of Canada|2009}}

===Federal government branding===
The national colours are used in federal government branding as part of the Federal Identity Program. This includes the use of the Canadian flag in the [[Federal Identity Program#Canada wordmark|Canada wordmark]], the "global identifier of the Government of Canada" specified in technical specification T-130.{{sfn|Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat: Canada Wordmark|2012}}

===Decorations===
The [[Canadian Forces Decoration]] ribbon consists of four red bars separated by equally spaced thin white lines.{{sfn|Department of National Defence|2004}} The [[Canada Medal]] instituted on 14 October 1943 was specified to have a ribbon in the national colours,{{sfn|McCreery|2005|p=73}} which was the same ribbon used for the Canada General Service Medal.{{sfn|Veterans Affairs Canada|2013}} The ill-fated medal was never awarded, and was abolished in 1966 with the introduction of the [[Order of Canada]],{{sfn|McCreery|2008}} which also has a red and white ribbon.

===Sport===
The [[Toronto Blue Jays]], a franchise in [[Major League Baseball]], honour [[Canada Day]] by wearing an [[Third jersey|alternate jersey]] instead of the team's usual [[Major League Baseball uniforms|uniform]].{{sfn|Creamer}} In the 1990s, the team would wear red [[baseball cap]]s,{{sfn|CNN Sports Illustrated|1999}} or a red uniform.{{sfn|Creamer|2005}} In 2012, the team wore a red uniform with white lettering.{{sfn|Creamer|2012}}

The Canadian national colours, and the de facto third colour black, are used prominently by [[ice hockey]] teams representing the nation, including the [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|men's ice hockey team]], [[Canada men's national junior ice hockey team|men's junior ice hockey team]], [[Canada men's national under-18 ice hockey team|men's under-18 ice hockey team]], [[Canada men's national ice sledge hockey team|men's ice sledge hockey team]], [[Canada men's national inline hockey team|men's inline hockey team]], [[Canada women's national ice hockey team|women's ice hockey team]], and [[Canada women's national under-18 ice hockey team|women's under-18 ice hockey team]]. The logo of [[Hockey Canada]], the national governing body for ice hockey in Canada, is red, white, and black, though their specifications are different from those of the national colours.{{sfn|Hockey Canada}}

