* {{IPA|/n, t, d/}} are [[Laminal consonant|laminal]] {{IPA|[n̻, t̻, d̻]}}, either [[Alveolar consonant|alveolar]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n}}, {{IPA link|t}}, {{IPA link|d}}]}} or [[Denti-alveolar consonant|denti-alveolar]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n̪}}, {{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=22}}
* {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} are aspirated fully voiceless {{IPA|[{{IPA link|p}}ʰ, {{IPA link|t}}ʰ, {{IPA link|k}}ʰ]}}, whereas {{IPA|/b, d, ɡ/}} are unaspirated, either fully voiceless {{IPA|[{{IPA link|p}}˭, {{IPA link|t}}˭, {{IPA link|k}}˭]}} or partially voiced {{IPA|[{{IPA link|b|b̥}}˭, {{IPA link|d|d̥}}˭, {{IPA link|ɡ|ɡ̊}}˭]}}. After {{IPA|/s/}} within the same syllable, only unaspirated voiceless stops occur.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=22}}
* {{IPA|/s/}} is dentalized laminal alveolar {{IPAblink|s̪}} or (uncommonly) non-retracted apical alveolar {{IPAblink|s̺}}.{{sfnp|Skaug|2003|pp=130–131}}
* {{IPA|/ʂ/}} is pronounced with protruded lips {{IPA|[ʂʷ]}}. The degree of protrusion depends on the rounding of the following vowel.{{sfnp|Popperwell|2010|p=58}}
* {{IPA|/h/}} is a (usually voiceless) fricative. The friction is normally glottal {{IPAblink|h}}, but sometimes it is dorsal: palatal {{IPAblink|ç}} when near front vowels, velar {{IPAblink|x}} near back vowels. It can be voiced {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɦ}} ~ {{IPA link|ʝ}} ~ {{IPA link|ɣ}}]}} between two voiced sounds.{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|p=40}}
* {{IPA|/ʋ, l, j, ɾ/}} are partially voiced or fully voiceless {{IPA|[{{IPA link|f}}, {{IPA link|l̥}}, {{IPA link|ç}}, {{IPA link|ɾ̥}}]}} when they occur after {{IPA|/p, t, k, f/}} (but not when {{IPA|/s/}} precedes within the same syllable). The flap {{IPA|/ɾ/}} is also partially voiced or fully voiceless when it occurs postvocalically before {{IPA|/p, k, f/}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=75–76, 79}}
* The approximants {{IPA|/ʋ, j/}} may be realized as fricatives {{IPA|[{{IPA link|v}}, {{IPA link|ʝ}}]}}:{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=74}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|p=41}}
** {{IPA|/ʋ/}} is sometimes a fricative, especially before a pause and in emphatic pronunciation.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=74}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|p=41}}
** There is not an agreement about the frequency of occurrence of the fricative allophone of {{IPA|/j/}}:
*** {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} states that {{IPA|/j/}} is sometimes a fricative.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=74}}
*** {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}} states that the fricative variant of {{IPA|/j/}} occurs often, especially before and after close vowels and in energetic pronunciation.{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|p=41}}
* {{IPA|/l/}} is in process of changing from laminal denti-alveolar {{IPAblink|l̪}} to [[Apical consonant|apical]] alveolar {{IPAblink|l|l̺}}, which leads to neutralization with the retroflex allophone {{IPA|[ɭ]}}. Laminal realization is still possible before vowels, after front and close vowels and after consonants that are not [[Coronal consonant|coronal]], and is obligatory after {{IPA|/n, t, d/}}. A velarized laminal {{IPAblink|ɫ|ɫ̪}} occurs after mid back vowels {{IPA|/ɔ, oː/}}, open back vowels {{IPA|/ɑ, ɑː/}}, and sometimes also after the close back vowels {{IPA|/ʊ, uː/}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=24–25}} However, {{Harvcoltxt|Endresen|1990}} states that at least in Oslo, the laminal variant is not velarized, and the difference is only between an apical and a laminal realization.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Endresen|1990|p=177}}, cited in {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000|p=25}}</ref>
* {{IPA|/ɾ/}} is an voiced apical alveolar [[Flap consonant|flap]] {{IPAblink|ɾ|ɾ̺}}. It is occasionally trilled {{IPAblink|r}}, e.g. in emphatic speech.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=24}}
* Retroflex allophones {{IPA|[ɳ, ʈ, ɖ]}} have been variously described as apical alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n|n̺}}, {{IPA link|t|t̺}}, {{IPA link|d|d̺}}]}} and apical [[Postalveolar consonant|postalveolar]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɲ|n̠}}, {{IPA link|t̠}}, {{IPA link|d̠}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=22}}
* {{IPA|/ɽ/}} alternates with {{IPA|/ɾ/}} in many words, but there is a small number of words in which only {{IPA|/ɽ/}} occurs.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=24}}
* {{IPA|/ŋ, k, ɡ/}} are [[Velar consonant|velar]], whereas {{IPA|/j/}} is [[Palatal consonant|palatal]].{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=22}} 
* {{IPA|/ç/}} may be palatal {{IPAblink|ç}}, but is often [[Alveolo-palatal consonant|alveolo-palatal]] {{IPAblink|ɕ}} instead. It is unstable in many dialects, and younger speakers in Bergen, Stavanger and Oslo merge {{IPA|/ç/}} with {{IPA|/ʂ/}} into {{IPAblink|ʂ}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=23}}
* Glottal stop {{IPAblink|ʔ}} may be inserted before word-initial vowels. In very emphatic speech, it can also be inserted word-medially in stressed syllables beginning with a vowel.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=22–23}}

Most of the [[retroflex consonant|retroflex]] (and [[postalveolar consonant|postalveolar]]) consonants are mutations of {{IPA|[ɾ]}}+any other [[alveolar consonant|alveolar]]/[[dental consonant]]; rn {{IPA|/ɾn/}} > {{IPA|[ɳ]}}, rt {{IPA|/ɾt/}} > {{IPA|[ʈ]}}, rl {{IPA|/ɾl/}} > {{IPA|[ɭ]}}, rs {{IPA|/ɾs/}} > {{IPA|[ʂ]}}, etc. {{IPA|/ɾd/}} across word boundaries ([[sandhi]]), in loanwords and in a group of primarily literary words may be pronounced {{IPA|[ɾd]}}, ''e.g.'', {{lang|no|verden}} {{IPA|[ˈʋæɾdn̩]}}, but it may also be pronounced {{IPA|[ɖ]}} in some dialects. Most of the dialects in Eastern, Central and Northern Norway use the retroflex consonants. Most Southern and Western dialects do not have these retroflex sounds, because in these areas a [[guttural]] realization of the {{IPA|/r/}} phoneme is commonplace, and seems to be expanding. Depending on phonetic context [[voiceless uvular fricative|voiceless]] ({{IPA|[χ]}}) or [[voiced uvular fricative]]s ({{IPA|[ʁ]}}) are used. (See map at right.) Other possible pronunciations include a [[uvular approximant]] {{IPA|[ʁ̞]}} or, more rarely, a [[uvular trill]] {{IPA|[ʀ]}}. There is, however, a small number of dialects that use both the uvular {{IPA|/r/}} ''and'' the retroflex allophones.

The [[retroflex flap]], {{IPA|[ɽ]}}, colloquially known to Norwegians as ''tjukk l'' ('thick l'), is a Central Scandinavian innovation that exists in Eastern Norwegian (including ''[[Trøndersk]]''), the southmost Northern dialects, and the most eastern Western Norwegian dialects. It is supposedly non-existent in most Western and Northern dialects. Today there is doubtlessly distinctive opposition between {{IPA|/ɽ/}} and {{IPA|/l/}} in the dialects that do have {{IPA|/ɽ/}}, e.g. ''gard'' {{IPA|/ɡɑːɽ/}} 'farm' and ''gal'' {{IPA|/ɡɑːl/}} 'crazy' in many Eastern Norwegian dialects.  Although  traditionally an Eastern Norwegian dialect phenomenon, it was considered vulgar, and for a long time it was avoided. Nowadays it is considered standard in the Eastern and Central Norwegian dialects,{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=6–11}} but is still clearly avoided in high-prestige sociolects or standardized speech. This avoidance calls into question the status of {{IPA|/ɽ/}} as a phoneme in certain sociolects.

According to [[Nina Grønnum]], ''tjukk l'' in Trøndersk is actually a postalveolar ''lateral'' flap {{IPAblink|ɺ|ɺ̠}}.{{sfnp|Grønnum|2005|p=155}}

