* Unless preceding another vowel within the same word, all unstressed vowels are short.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=19}}
* In unstressed syllables, {{IPA|/ɛ/}} tends to reduce to a simple schwa {{IPAblink|ə}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=20-21}}
* The phonemic status of {{IPAblink|æ}} and {{IPAblink|æː}} in Urban East Norwegian is unclear since these pattern as [[allophone]]s of, respectively, {{IPA|/ɛ/}} and {{IPA|/eː/}} before the flaps {{IPA|/ɾ/}} and {{IPA|/ɽ/}}. However, there also are words in which {{IPA|/eː/}} is realized as {{IPAblink|eː}} despite the following flap, such as ''Per'' {{IPA|[peːɾ]}} 'Peter'. {{IPAblink|æ}} also occurs in the diphthongs {{IPA|[æɪ]}} and {{IPA|[æʉ]}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=14, 106}}
* Urban East Norwegian also features a few non-phonemic diphthongs, which are {{IPA|[œʏ, ɔʏ, æɪ, æʉ, ɑɪ]}}. {{IPA|[œʏ, ɔʏ, æɪ, ɑɪ]}} can be analyzed as sequences of {{IPA|/œ, ɔ, ɛ, ɑ/}} and {{IPA|/j/}} which is allophonically labialized to {{IPAblink|ɥ}} after rounded vowels. {{IPA|[æʉ]}} can be analyzed as a sequence of {{IPA|/ɛ/}} and {{IPA|/w/}} (which corresponds to the central {{IPAblink|ʉ̞|ʉ}}, not back {{IPAblink|ʊ͍|ʊ}}).{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17, 19, 25}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|p=22}}
** The second element of {{IPA|/ɛw/}} is often realized as labiodental {{IPAblink|ʋ}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=19}}
** Some speakers have an additional diphthong {{IPA|[ɛɪ]}} in their inventory which, like {{IPA|[ɔʏ]}} and {{IPA|[ɑɪ]}}, is restricted to loanwords. For such speakers, {{IPA|[æɪ]}} is best analyzed as {{IPA|/æ/}} + {{IPA|/j/}}, whereas {{IPA|/ɛj/}} is the phonemic representation of the marginal {{IPA|[ɛɪ]}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=19}}
** Another (very rare) diphthong is {{IPA|[ʉɪ]}} (phonemically {{IPA|/ʉj/}}), which appears only in the word ''hui'' ('haste').{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=19}}

The following sections describe each monophthong in detail.

====Symbols====
* The vowels {{IPA|/iː, yː, ʉː, eː, ɔ, æ, æː/}} as well as the {{IPAblink|ə}} allophone of {{IPA|/ɛ/}} are invariably transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|iː, yː, ʉː, eː, ɔ, æ, æː}}}} and {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ə}}}}.<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} or {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}}.</ref>
* {{IPA|/uː, øː/}} are most often transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|uː, øː}}}},<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Krech et al.|2009}}.</ref> but {{IPA|/uː/}} may be transcribed with an obsolete {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɷː}}}} by older sources.<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}}.</ref> In addition, {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} uses both {{angle bracket|{{IPA|øː}}}} and {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɵː}}}} for {{IPA|/øː/}}. This article transcribes those vowels with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|uː, øː}}}}.
* {{IPA|/oː/}} is most often transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɔː}}}},<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Krech et al.|2009}}.</ref> yet this article uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|oː}}}}, following {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}}.<ref>This article uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|oː}}}} because other mid vowels (that is, {{IPA|/eː/}} and {{IPA|/øː/}}) are also transcribed with ''close-mid'' symbols. Urban East Norwegian {{IPA|/oː/}} is also never as open as {{IPAblink|ɔː}} as it has been variously described as mid {{IPAblink|o̞ː}} ({{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 17}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=4}}) and close-mid back {{IPAblink|oː}} ({{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17}}).</ref>
* The open back {{IPA|/ɑ, ɑː/}} are most often transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɑ, ɑː}}}},<ref>For example by {{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Krech et al.|2009}}.</ref> but {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}} transcribes them with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|a, aː}}}}. This article uses the former set.
* The short close vowels {{IPA|/ɪ, ʏ, ʉ, ʊ/}} are transcribed with either {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɪ, ʏ, ʉ, ʊ}}}} or {{angle bracket|{{IPA|i, y, ʉ, u}}}}. The short {{IPA|/ʉ/}} is occasionally transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ʉ̞}}}} or a non-IPA symbol {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ᵿ}}}} instead, whereas {{IPA|/ʊ/}} is transcribed with an obsolete symbol {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɷ}}}} in some older sources.<ref>Sources that use {{angle bracket|{{IPA|i, y, u}}}} include {{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}}. {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} also uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|i, y, u}}}}, but admits that {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɪ, ʏ, ʊ}}}} is just as correct a transcription (see p. 11). Sources that use {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɪ, ʏ, ʊ}}}} include {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}}. Some sources mix these sets, e.g. {{Harvcoltxt|Krech et al.|2009}} uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|i, ʏ, u}}}}. The short close central vowel is transcribed with {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ʉ}}}} by most sources, but {{Harvcoltxt|Krech et al.|2009}} use a non-IPA symbol {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ᵿ}}}}. {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} also mentions {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ʉ̞}}}} as a possible transcription. Sources that use {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɷ}}}} for {{IPA|/ʊ/}} include {{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}}.</ref> This article uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɪ, ʏ, ʉ, ʊ}}}}.
* The short mid front vowels {{IPA|/ɛ, œ/}} are transcribed with either {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɛ, œ}}}} or {{angle bracket|{{IPA|e, ø}}}}.<ref>Sources that use {{angle bracket|{{IPA|e, ø}}}} include {{Harvcoltxt|Vanvik|1979}}. Sources that use {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɛ, œ}}}} include {{Harvcoltxt|Kristoffersen|2000}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}}. Some sources mix these sets, e.g. {{Harvcoltxt|Haugen|1974}} uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɛ, ø}}}} whereas {{Harvcoltxt|Krech et al.|2009}} uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|e, œ}}}}.</ref> This article uses {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɛ, œ}}}}.

====Phonetic realization====
* {{IPA|/ɪ, iː, ɛ, eː, æ, æː, ɑ, ɑː/}} are unrounded, whereas {{IPA|/ʏ, yː, ʉ, ʉː, ʊ, uː, œ, øː, ɔ, oː/}} are rounded:
** The close {{IPA|/ʏ, yː, ʉ, ʉː/}} have been variously described as protruded {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʏ̫}}, {{IPA link|y̫ː}}]}} and compressed {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʏ̈|ʉ͍}}, {{IPA link|ÿ|ʉ͍ː}}]}} as well as compressed {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʏ͍}}, {{IPA link|y͍ː}}]}} and protruded {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʉ̫˕|ʉ̫}}, {{IPA link|ʉ̫ː}}]}}. The backness of {{IPA|/ʉ, ʉː/}} has also been variously described as central {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʉ̞|ʉ}}, {{IPA link|ʉː}}]}} and near-front {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʏ|ʉ̟}}, {{IPA link|y|ʉ̟ː}}]}}. Therefore, {{IPA|/ʏ, yː/}} may be differentiated from {{IPA|/ʉ, ʉː/}} by backness and the type of rounding or even only by the type of rounding.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=15–16}}
** The close back {{IPA|/ʊ, uː/}} are compressed {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʊ͍}}, {{IPA link|u͍ː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Haugen|1974|p=40}}{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=16}}
** The mid {{IPA|/œ, øː, ɔ, oː/}} are protruded {{IPA|[{{IPA link|œ̫}}, {{IPA link|ø̫ː}}, {{IPA link|ɒ|ɔ̫}}, {{IPA link|o|o̫ː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Haugen|1974|p=40}}
* The height and backness of Norwegian vowels is as follows:
** {{IPA|/ɪ, ʏ, ʉ, ʊ/}} have been variously described as near-close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʏ}}, {{IPA link|ʉ̞}}, {{IPA link|ʊ͍|ʊ}}]}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13-14, 18-20}} and close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|y}}, {{IPA link|ʉ}}, {{IPA link|u͍|u}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=2}} In addition, {{IPA|/ɪ/}} and {{IPA|/ʊ/}} are more peripheral than the canonical values of IPA {{angbr|{{IPA|ɪ, ʊ}}}} ({{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ|ɪ̟}} ~ {{IPA link|i}}]}} and {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʊ͍|ʊ̠}} ~ {{IPA link|u͍|u}}]}}, respectively).{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=2}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13-14, 18}}
** {{IPA|/iː, yː, ʉː, uː/}} are phonetically close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|iː}}, {{IPA link|yː}}, {{IPA link|ʉː}}, {{IPA link|u͍|uː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13-14, 17-19}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=4}}
** {{IPA|/ɛ/}} is mid front {{IPAblink|ɛ̝}}.{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=2}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 15}}
** {{IPA|/eː, øː/}} are close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eː}}, {{IPA link|ø̫|øː}}]}}. {{IPA|/eː/}} is front,{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=4}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13-14}} yet {{IPA|/øː/}} has been variously described as front {{IPAblink|ø̫|øː}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=4}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 20}} and central {{IPAblink|ɵː}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17, 33–35, 37, 343}}
** {{IPA|/œ/}} has been variously described as open-mid front {{IPAblink|œ̫|œ}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=2}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 20}} and mid central {{IPAblink|ɞ̝}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17}}
** {{IPA|/ɔ/}} has been variously described as near-open back {{IPAblink|ɒ|ɔ̞}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=2}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 17}} and close-mid back {{IPAblink|o}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17}}
** {{IPA|/oː/}} has been variously described as mid back {{IPAblink|o̞ː}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|p=4}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 17}} and close-mid back {{IPAblink|oː}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17}}
** {{IPA|/æ, æː/}} have been variously described as near-open front {{IPA|[{{IPA link|æ}}, {{IPA link|æː}}]}}{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=13, 15}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|pp=2, 4}} and open central {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ä}}, {{IPA link|äː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17}}
** {{IPA|/ɑ, ɑː/}} are open back {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɑ}}, {{IPA link|ɑː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|pp=16–17}}{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|pp=2, 4}}
* {{IPA|/eː, øː/}} are frequently realized as centering diphthongs {{IPA|[eə, øə]}}. {{IPA|/iː, yː, uː, oː/}} can also be realized as {{IPA|[iə, yə, uə, oə]}}, yet {{IPA|/ʉː, æː, ɑː/}} are always monophthongal.{{sfnp|Vanvik|1979|pp=14, 17, 19-20}}{{sfnp|Strandskogen|1979|p=16}} However, according to {{Harvcoltxt|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005}}, the diphthongal variants of {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} are opening {{IPA|[eɛ, øœ, oɑ]}}, not centering.{{sfnp|Kvifte|Gude-Husken|2005|pp=4–5}}

==Accent==
[[Image:Map of the major tonal dialects of Norwegian and Swedish.png|frame|right|Map of the major tonal dialects of Norwegian and Swedish, from {{Harvcoltxt|Riad|2014}}.<br />• Dark areas have a low tone in accent 2, whereas the light areas have a high tone in accent 2.<br />• The isogloss marks the boundary between connective and non-connective dialects. East and north of it, all of the compounds get accent 2, whereas west and south of the isogloss, compounds vary in accent. <br><br>Note that contrary to the information in the map, the dialects of [[Rogaland]], [[Aust-Agder]] and [[Trøndelag]] are not traditionally classified as East Norwegian, but as [[Vestlandsk|West Norwegian]], South Norwegian and [[Trøndersk]], respectively.]]

Norwegian is a [[pitch accent]] language with two distinct pitch patterns. They are used to differentiate polysyllabic words with otherwise identical pronunciation. Although difference in spelling occasionally allows the words to be distinguished in the written language (such as ''bønner''/''bønder''), in most cases the minimal pairs are written alike. For example, in most Norwegian dialects, the word {{lang|no|uttale}} ('pronounce') is pronounced using tone 1 ({{IPA|[ˈʉːttɑːlə]}}), while {{lang|no|uttale}} ('pronunciation') uses tone 2 ({{IPA|[²ʉːttɑːlə]}}).

There are significant variations in the realization of the pitch accent between dialects. In most of Eastern Norway, including the capital Oslo, the so-called low pitch dialects are spoken. In these dialects, accent 1 uses a low flat pitch in the first syllable, while accent 2 uses a high, sharply falling pitch in the first syllable and a low pitch in the beginning of the second syllable. In both accents, these pitch movements are followed by a rise of [[Intonation (linguistics)|intonation]]al nature (phrase accent), the size (and presence) of which signals emphasis/focus and which corresponds in function to the normal accent in languages that lack [[tone (linguistics)|lexical tone]], such as English. That rise culminates in the final syllable of an accentual phrase, while the fall to utterance-final low pitch that is so common in most languages{{sfnp|Gussenhoven|2004|p=89}} is either very small or absent.

On the other hand, in most of western and northern Norway (the so-called high-pitch dialects) accent 1 is falling, while accent 2 is rising in the first syllable and falling in the second syllable or somewhere around the syllable boundary. The two tones can be transcribed on the first vowel as {{IPA|/ɑ̀/}} for accent 1 and {{IPA|/ɑ̂/}} for accent 2; the modern reading of the IPA (low and falling) corresponds to eastern Norway, whereas an older tradition of using diacritics to represent the shape of the pitch trace (falling and rising-falling) corresponds to western Norway.

Accent 1 generally occurs in words that were monosyllabic in [[Old Norse]], and accent 2 in words that were polysyllabic.

=== Tonal accents and morphology ===
In many dialects, the accents take on a significant role in marking grammatical categories. Thus, the ending ''(T1)—en'' implies determinate form of a masculine monosyllabic noun ({{lang|no|båten}} 'boat', {{lang|no|bilen}}, 'car'), whereas ''(T2)-en'' denotes either determinate form of a masculine bisyllabic noun or an adjectivised noun/verb ({{lang|no|moden}} 'mature'). Similarly, the ending ''(T1)—a'' denotes feminine singular determinate monosyllabic nouns ({{lang|no|boka}} 'book', {{lang|no|rota}} 'root') or neuter plural determinate nouns ({{lang|no|husa}} 'houses', {{lang|no|lysa}} 'lights'), whereas the ending ''(T2)—a'' denotes the [[preterite]] of weak verbs ({{lang|no|rota}} 'made a mess', {{lang|no|husa}} 'housed'), feminine singular determinate bisyllabic nouns ({{lang|no|bøtta}} 'bucket', {{lang|no|ruta}} 'square').

In Eastern Norwegian the tone difference may also be applied to groups of words, with different meaning as a result. ''Gro igjen'' for example, means 'grow anew' when pronounced with tone 1 {{IPA|[ˈɡɾùː‿ɪjə́n]}}, but 'grow over' when pronounced with tone 2 {{IPA|[ˈɡɾûː‿ɪjə́n]}}. In other parts of Norway, this difference is achieved instead by the shift of stress ('''''gro''' igjen'' {{IPA|[ˈɡɾuː ɪjən]}} vs. ''gro i'''gjen''''' {{IPA|[ɡɾuː ˈɪjən]}}).

=== In compound words ===
In a compound word, the pitch accent is lost on one of the elements of the compound (the one with weaker or [[secondary stress]]), but the erstwhile tonic syllable retains the full length (long vowel or geminate consonant) of a stressed syllable.{{sfnp|Kristoffersen|2000|p=184}}

=== Monosyllabic tonal accents ===
In some dialects of Norwegian, mainly those from [[Nordmøre]] and [[Trøndelag]] to [[Lofoten]], there may also be tonal opposition in monosyllables, as in {{IPA|[bîːl]}} ('car') ''vs.'' {{IPA|[bìːl]}} ('axe'). In a few dialects, mainly in and near [[Nordmøre]], the monosyllabic tonal opposition is also represented in final syllables with secondary stress, as well as double tone designated to single syllables of primary stress in polysyllabic words. In practice, this means that one gets minimal pairs like: {{IPA|[hɑ̀ːnɪɲː]}} ('the rooster') ''vs.'' {{IPA|[hɑ̀ːnɪ̂ɲː]}} ('get him inside'); {{IPA|[brʏ̂ɲːɑ]}} ('in the well') ''vs.'' {{IPA|[brʏ̂ɲːɑ̂]}} ('her well'); {{IPA|[læ̂nsmɑɲː]}} ('sheriff') ''vs.'' {{IPA|[læ̂nsmɑ̂ɲː]}} ('the sheriff'). Amongst the various views on how to interpret this situation, the most promising one may be that the words displaying these complex tones have an extra [[mora (linguistics)|mora]]. This mora may have little or no effect on duration and dynamic stress, but is represented as a tonal dip.

Other dialects with tonal opposition in monosyllabic words have done away with vowel length opposition. Thus, the words {{IPA|[vɔ̀ːɡ]}} ('dare') ''vs.'' {{IPA|[vɔ̀ɡː]}} ('cradle') have merged into {{IPA|[vɔ̀ːɡ]}} in the dialect of [[Oppdal]].

=== Loss of tonal accents ===
Some forms of Norwegian have lost the tonal accent opposition. This includes mainly parts of the area around (but not including) Bergen; the [[Brønnøysund]] area; to some extent, the dialect of [[Bodø]]; and, also to various degrees, many dialects between [[Tromsø]] and the [[Russia]]n border. [[Faroese language|Faroese]] and [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]], which have their main historical origin in [[Old Norse]], also show no tonal opposition. It is, however, not clear whether these languages lost the tonal accent or whether the tonal accent was not yet there when these languages started their separate development. Standard Danish, Rigsdansk, replaces tonal accents with the stød, whilst some southern, insular dialects of Danish preserve the tonal accent to different degrees. The Finland Swedish dialects also lack a tonal accent, as no such phenomenon exists in Finnish.

=== Pulmonic ingressive ===
The words {{lang|no|ja}} ('yes') and {{lang|no|nei}} ('nei') are sometimes pronounced with inhaled breath ([[pulmonic ingressive]]) in Norwegian—and this can be rather confusing for foreigners. The same phenomenon occurs across the other Scandinavian languages, and can also be found in German, French, Finnish and Japanese, to name a few.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}

